04468nam a22005775i 9780300195200DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001952007 a10.12987/97803001952002doi  a(DE-B1597)485903  a(OCoLC)841809188  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aE169.1b.M264 2013 7aHIS0360702bisacsh04a973.932231 aMargulies, Joseph, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Changed When Everything Changed :b9/11 and the Making of National Identity /cJoseph Margulies. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. “What the United States of America Is All About at Our Core” -- tPART I. Making National Identity -- t2. “The Ceaseless Striving to Live Out Our True Creed” -- t3. The Dark Side of the Creed -- tPART II. History Makes No Sharp Turns -- t4. Race and Religion in National Identity -- t5. The Punitive Turn -- tPART III. Preservation and Transformation -- t6. “A Fight for Our Principles” -- t7. “We Need to Bring the News to People” -- t8. “A War for the Survival of America” -- t9. “Think the Unthinkable” -- t10. “Can You Think of Anything More Un-American?” -- t11. “Must We Sell Our Birthright?” -- t12. The Paradox of the Obama Era -- t13. All Will Be as It Ought to Be -- tNotes -- tPermissions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeautifully written and carefully reasoned, this bold and provocative work upends the conventional wisdom about the American reaction to crisis. Margulies demonstrates that for key elements of the post-9/11 landscape—especially support for counterterror policies like torture and hostility to Islam—American identity is not only darker than it was before September 11, 2001, but substantially more repressive than it was immediately after the attacks. These repressive attitudes, Margulies shows us, have taken hold even as the terrorist threat has diminished significantly. Contrary to what is widely imagined, at the moment of greatest perceived threat, when the fear of another attack “hung over the country like a shroud,” favorable attitudes toward Muslims and Islam were at record highs, and the suggestion that America should torture was denounced in the public square. Only much later did it become socially acceptable to favor “enhanced interrogation” and exhibit clear anti-Muslim prejudice. Margulies accounts for this unexpected turn and explains what it means to the nation’s identity as it moves beyond 9/11. We express our values in the same language, but that language can hide profound differences and radical changes in what we actually believe. “National identity,” he writes, “is not fixed, it is made.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNational characteristics, American. 0aNationalismzUnited States. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001xInfluence. 0aTerrorismxPreventionxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030017655140uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030019520040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300195200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300195200/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY